[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Optimizing fetch tests**\n\nI’m thinking about needing to reduce the loop for testing, but I can’t change the upstream. The current wrapper runs 400 fetches across 20 partitions, which feels slow. I wonder if I can create a lighter test to cover the same anonymous class. There’s definitely a one-to-one mapping here. I can't change the source, but could I adapt the environment? Maybe adjusting timeout settings or JVM arguments could help? I need to figure this out!\n\n**Optimizing bytecode generation**\n\nI need to focus on improving the performance in InvokerBytecodeGenerator. There's this property `java.lang.invoke.MethodHandle.CUSTOMIZE_THRESHOLD` with a default of 127. I'm wondering if setting it to -1 would disable customization. However, if the threshold is 0, it compiles immediately. We might want to avoid using the upstream method and directly test the dynamic-access site instead. Since the current goal is the KafkaFuture class, I should ensure all tests pass, considering disabling problematic ones if necessary. Ah, so many rules to navigate!\n\n**Adjusting coverage expectations**\n\nIt seems like there's an expectation to maintain full coverage without skipping any tests. I need to keep the dynamic-access coverage for each class intact because removing tests would lower that coverage, which isn't ideal. I'm thinking about adjusting the timeout for the Fetcher test to 59 seconds. That could help manage performance without sacrificing coverage, right? It's a delicate balance, but I want to make sure we meet those expectations while keeping everything covered effectively.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_08e00024690e9867016a0f4eec6a98819083b41beae043b4fa\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqD072pr4c5Sed0OZ3U_amyMvF_NLc6yiA7HI0Y1f_FqaGzNH6iHRhOJ71phHIjVUY_0Qb8fJK5HBVKPVhCmFi9F3bJ3sSEgbFavlRR6JjZDv5nUF7ruqXGKNQCpqESDN5ldpGJFHtNTeaa2